Use Command Prompt to navigate to the folder where you want the project:
cd <your folder path>
Open the FacialRecognitionDoor.sln solution file, in the FacialRecognitionDoor folder you just downloaded, using Visual Studio 2015.
On the right panel, under the "FacialRecognitionDoor" project, navigate to the Constants.cs file. You should see a section at the top entitled "General Constants". The first thing you need to do here is enter your Oxford API key. Follow the instructions here to acquire your key.
Replace OXFORD_KEY_HERE with your new key:
https://hackster.imgix.net/uploads/image/file/107780/ConstantsAPIKeyScreenshot.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat&w=740&h=555&fit=max
ONLY FOR MINNOWBOARD MAX: Switch the DisableLiveCameraFeed variable from true to false:
https://hackster.imgix.net/uploads/image/file/107782/Facial-Recognition-Door_Constants_cs_at_develop_%C2%B7_ethankusters_Facial-Recognition-Door.png?auto=compress%2Cformat&w=740&h=555&fit=max
On the top menu of Visual Studio, select Debug and ARM if you are using a Raspberry Pi. If you're using an MBM, select Debug and x86.
https://hackster.imgix.net/uploads/image/file/107677/cs-remote-machine-debugging.png?auto=compress%2Cformat&w=740&h=555&fit=max
Press Remote Machine. In the "Remote Connections" dialog you will have to enter your Remote Machine IP address and use "Universal (Unencrypted Protocol)" for Authentication Mode
Use WindowsIoTCoreWatcher to find your IP address.
https://hackster.imgix.net/uploads/image/file/107679/cs-remote-connections.PNG?auto=compress%2Cformat&w=740&h=555&fit=max
You can now run the code! Press the Remote Machine button with the green "play" arrow.
